<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n12030j"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12030j">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12030j"> 30(j)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> heart with parchment / (ex voto)</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Une des cuves contenait exclusivement tous les c&oelig;urs d&apos;or, d&apos;argent et de cuivre que les fid&egrave;les p&egrave;lerins, au cours de ces si&egrave;cles, avaient accumul&eacute;s autour de l&apos;Archange, en reconnaissance de gr&acirc;ces obtenues. <p>Le c&oelig;ur &eacute;tait, en effet, l&apos;ex-voto le plus offert. Il &eacute;tait g&eacute;n&eacute;ralement surmont&eacute; d&apos;une petite croix ou d&apos;une flamme, entour&eacute; d&apos;une couronne d&apos;&eacute;pines, incrust&eacute; de fleurs ou d&apos;initiales; souvent, il &eacute;tait creux; il s&apos;ouvrait alors comme une montre, et &agrave; l&apos;int&eacute;rieur, on mettait un petit morceau de parchemin sur lequel on avait &eacute;crit l&apos;objet du v&oelig;u form&eacute; ou exauc&eacute;. Il y avait des c&oelig;urs en or avec des pierres pr&eacute;cieuses; d&apos;autres &eacute;taient en argent, de tr&egrave;s nombreux en cuivre, en beau cuivre jaune, en or de Villedieu, comme on dit dans cette partie de la Normandie, o&ugrave; depuis des si&egrave;cles, on travaille ce m&eacute;tal pour en faire des chaudrons et des po&ecirc;les. <br><font color="green">[One of the cellars contained only all the gold, silver and copper hearts that the pious pilgrims, in the course of the centuries, had collected around the Archangel, as proof of the grace they had received. The heart was really the most popular ex-voto. There was generally a little cross on the top or a flame, surrounded by a crown of thorns, inlaid with flowers or initials; often, they were hollow; they opened then like a watch and inside you could place a piece of vellum on which one could write the object of a wish asked or fulfilled. There were golden hearts or hearts with precious stones; others were made of silver, lots in copper, a beautiful yellow copper, in gold from Villedieu, as they say in Normandy, where this metal has been worked for centuries to make pots and pans out of it.]</font> <small> &Eacute;tienne Dupont, <a name="LMSM" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#LMSM"><cite title="source">Les l&eacute;gendes du Mont-Saint-Michel</cite></a> (1924) 120</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
